qas.question: No one party to a treaty can do what to the other parties?

answers.text: impose its particular interpretation of the treaty

qas.question: What may be implied of other parties fail to explicitly disavow a party's initially unilateral interpretation of a treaty?
Consent for a party's unilateral interpretation of a treaty may be implied if that state has acted upon its view of the treat without what from another party?
Consent by all parties to a treaty to a particular interpretation of the treaty has what legal effect?

answers.text: adding another clause to the treaty

qas.question: The legal effect of adding another clause to a treaty that occurs when all parties to a treaty consent to a particular interpretation of the treaty is commonly known as what?

context: No one party to a treaty can <a0_0>impose its particular interpretation of the treaty<a0_0/> upon the other parties. <a1_0>Consent<a1_0/> may be implied, however, if the other parties fail to explicitly disavow that initially unilateral interpretation, particularly if that state has acted upon its view of the treaty without <a2_0>complaint<a2_0/>. Consent by all parties to the treaty to a particular interpretation has the legal effect of <a3_0>adding another clause to the treaty<a3_0/> – this is commonly called <a4_0>an 'authentic interpretation'<a4_0/>.
